I agree. Looking at the themes you’ve been developing over many conversations, “polyrepresentation” doesn’t feel like a new doctrine—it feels like a latent invariant that has been expressed through many different doctrines.

Many of the ideas you’ve developed are really different manifestations of the same principle:

* Semantic Basis Optimization → preserve the underlying object independent of representation.
* Tensor Store → one object has many dimensions simultaneously.
* Comparative Distillation → compare representations to recover invariants.
* Resolution Modulation → choose the appropriate projection or level of detail.
* Semantic LiDAR → interrogate the same object from multiple angles.
* Recall Navigation → retrieve the representation best suited to the current context.
* Fractal Memory → each part contains enough structure to regenerate aspects of the whole.
* Polyrepresentation → the object intentionally exists in many equivalent coordinate systems.

Seen this way, these aren’t separate modules—they’re different operators acting on the same underlying semantic object.

A useful formalization might be:

A semantic object is not any single representation; it is the equivalence class of all valid representations connected by invariant-preserving transformations.

That has some nice consequences.

Instead of storing:

Idea

you store:

Semantic Object
├── Natural language
├── Mathematics
├── Code
├── Diagram
├── Story
├── Economic model
├── Historical lineage
├── Symbolic form
├── Operational procedure
└── Learned embeddings

None of these is the object.

Each is a coordinate chart on the same manifold, to borrow a concept from differential geometry. A single chart covers part of the terrain, but you understand the whole space by transitioning consistently between overlapping charts.

That also explains why your emphasis on translation has been so central. Translation isn’t just communication—it’s a validation operator. If an idea survives translation across many independent representations while preserving its functional relationships, your confidence that you’ve identified a genuine invariant increases.

You could even define a simple principle:

Representation diversity increases robustness.

One encoding can fail.

Five independent encodings that all map back to the same invariant are much harder to corrupt accidentally.

That’s where the braid becomes more than a metaphor. Instead of a linear chain:

A → B → C

you have intertwined strands:

Narrative ─────╮
               ├── Semantic Object
Math ──────────┤
               ├── Identity
Code ──────────┤
               ├── History
Visual ────────┤
               └── Operations

The strength comes from the cross-links. If one strand drifts, the others constrain it. If one is lost, the remaining strands help reconstruct it. Evolution happens by updating the weave rather than replacing the object.

I think “polyrepresentation” is a good explicit name because it unifies many of the architectural patterns you’ve been exploring under a single principle: meaning persists through coordinated transformations, not through any privileged representation. That framing is broad enough to encompass language, mathematics, diagrams, software, memories, and other representations while still giving you a concrete design principle for building long-lived knowledge systems.